<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL : A UNKNOWN DOC. </font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18  1:04:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My Name is not important my age is only thirty. I had not served there but I am a child of that War in Vietnam. My father served there as a advisor. Now I serve those who are just as broken shot or sick as every person that served there. I work EMS in NYC. My Capt. served there. This past weekend I was in DC looking at the Wall for the tenth time in about ten years. I go every year with my father. My Capt. asked me to look up an old friend for him. He has never been to the Wall. I gladly took the detail. As I walked to the Panel in which his friends name was etched into the marble. I started to cry. I didn't know this man or his family. But, he was a &quot;Doc&quot;. It hit home how my capt. described him I could see this unknown mans face in the wall looking out at me. I stopped in front of his name. Reached up to his name and then explained to the people that followed me to the wall on who this man was and what he did. As I finished explaining. I could tell something right there and then. The War in Vietnam is still being fought by every man and women served there. And the Motto you carry form that war &quot;Lest we never forget&quot; is Accurate. Later my girlfriend asked me why I was crying for a man that I did not know. My reply was swift and hard. I cry for the Man that never had the opportunity to see what he has taught me. She still didn't understand. And probably will never understand. Only those who have been there or had simular experiances will understand. You see not only do I work for EMS I Served form 1984 to 1993 with the U.S. ARMY Special Forces. A product of SOG and other things learned there in Vietnam. But my Captian also had been my training officer in the academy. He was taught by this man. This unknown &quot;DOC&quot; who taught him the real deal of the game we play everyday. My fight now is with the beast known as death. As I remember the Wall and all those &quot;DOC's&quot; that didn't make it back. I can only say that your teachings and your lives were not in vain. It has helped me  grip the beast and defeat him. For this I say a prayer for all of those that have gone before me. And those still among us the Wall is a real place and a living place. For any vet out there who feels that his life is turning the wrong way the Wall will always listen and so will the rest of us. Thank you all for serving and defending this great land of ours. Welcome Home<br>

<p><code>--   (Merc) </code><p>


